    "trap": "Part (b) baits the lazy bound. Since each $\\sin^{2}\\le 1$, a solver writes $\\sin^{2}A+\\sin^{2}B+\\sin^{2}C\\le 3$, then tries to push two angles to $\\tfrac\\pi2$ to drive two terms to $1$ and declares the supremum to be (near) $3$. But the constraint $A+B+C=\\pi$ couples the three angles: forcing $A,B\\to\\tfrac\\pi2$ forces $C\\to 0$, so $\\sin^{2}C\\to 0$ and the sum actually collapses to $2$ — below the equilateral value $\\tfrac94$, not above it. The three $\\sin^2$ terms are not free to be bounded one at a time. The honest engine is part (a): $\\sin^{2}A+\\sin^{2}B+\\sin^{2}C=F+2\\cos A\\cos B\\cos C=2+2\\cos A\\cos B\\cos C$, so the sum is governed entirely by the single coupled quantity $\\cos A\\cos B\\cos C$, whose maximum is $\\tfrac18$ (equilateral) — giving max $2+\\tfrac14=\\tfrac94$, never $3$. Mistaking which quantity the constraint controls, or treating the squares as independent, returns the phantom bound $3$.",
