          "For (b), use the invariant as a substitution: maximising $g=\\sin^{2}A+\\sin^{2}B+\\sin^{2}C$ is the same as maximising $2+2\\cos A\\cos B\\cos C$, hence the same as maximising $P=\\cos A\\cos B\\cos C$.",
          "$P$ is non-positive unless the triangle is acute, so the maximiser is interior to the acute region; set up Lagrange multipliers on $h=A+B+C-\\pi=0$. Then $\\partial_A(\\cos A\\cos B\\cos C)=-\\sin A\\cos B\\cos C=\\lambda$ and cyclically, giving $\\sin A\\cos B\\cos C=\\sin B\\cos C\\cos A=\\sin C\\cos A\\cos B$. Dividing the first two by $\\cos C$ (nonzero, acute) yields $\\tan A=\\tan B$, and cyclically $\\tan B=\\tan C$, so $A=B=C=\\tfrac\\pi3$ is the unique critical point.",
