    "trap": "The seductive ``improvement'': start from $P=2^{-4}T_5=x^5-\\tfrac54 x^3+\\tfrac{5}{16}x$, whose graph oscillates between $+\\tfrac1{16}$ and $-\\tfrac1{16}$, and try to shave the positive peaks by subtracting a small constant $\\varepsilon>0$, i.e. take $Q=P-\\varepsilon$. The student reasons ``the $+\\tfrac1{16}$ maxima drop to $\\tfrac1{16}-\\varepsilon$, so $\\lVert Q\\rVert<\\tfrac1{16}$.'' This is wrong on two fronts. First, $Q$ is still monic (subtracting a constant cannot touch the $x^5$ term), so it IS a legal competitor — but its NEGATIVE peaks rise from $-\\tfrac1{16}$ to $-\\tfrac1{16}-\\varepsilon$, so $\\lVert Q\\rVert=\\tfrac1{16}+\\varepsilon$ INCREASES. The deeper trap is in the alternation count: one is tempted to think $T_5$ alternates at only $5$ points (one per ``hump'') and that a competitor merely needs to beat it at those $5$, whereas equioscillation happens at $n+1=6$ points, and it is exactly that extra alternation that forces the contradiction. Mis-counting $6$ as $5$ collapses ``$\\ge n$ sign changes'' to ``$\\ge n-1$,'' which a degree-$(n-1)$ difference polynomial can survive — so the whole proof silently fails.",
    "solutions": [
      {
        "name": "Equioscillation contradiction (the minimax theorem)",
        "steps": [
          "Set $P=2^{1-n}T_n$ with $n=5$, i.e. $P=\\tfrac1{16}T_5=x^5-\\tfrac54 x^3+\\tfrac5{16}x$. Since $T_5$ has leading coefficient $16=2^{n-1}$, $P$ is monic of degree $5$, and $|T_5|\\le1$ gives $\\lVert P\\rVert\\le\\tfrac1{16}$; the value $\\tfrac1{16}$ is attained, so $\\lVert P\\rVert=\\tfrac1{16}$. Thus $m\\le\\tfrac1{16}$.",
          "Suppose, for contradiction, some monic quintic $Q$ beats it: $\\lVert Q\\rVert<\\tfrac1{16}$. Form $D=P-Q$. Both are monic of degree $5$, so the $x^5$ terms cancel and $\\deg D\\le 4$.",
          "Evaluate $D$ at the $n+1=6$ Chebyshev alternation nodes $x_k=\\cos\\tfrac{k\\pi}{5}$, $k=0,\\dots,5$, where $P(x_k)=\\tfrac1{16}(-1)^k$. Since $|Q(x_k)|<\\tfrac1{16}$, the sign of $D(x_k)=P(x_k)-Q(x_k)$ is dominated by $P(x_k)$: $D(x_k)$ has the sign of $(-1)^k$.",
          "Hence $D$ takes the sign pattern $+,-,+,-,+,-$ across the six nodes: it changes sign on each of the $5$ consecutive intervals, so by the intermediate value theorem $D$ has at least $5$ distinct real roots in $[-1,1]$.",
          "But $\\deg D\\le 4$, so $D$ can have at most $4$ roots unless $D\\equiv 0$. A nonzero degree-$\\le4$ polynomial with $5$ roots is impossible, so $D\\equiv0$, i.e. $Q=P$ and $\\lVert Q\\rVert=\\tfrac1{16}$ — contradicting $\\lVert Q\\rVert<\\tfrac1{16}$.",
          "Therefore no monic quintic has sup-norm below $\\tfrac1{16}$, the bound is achieved by $P$, and the same root-counting (any minimiser $Q$ forces $D\\equiv0$) shows $P$ is the UNIQUE minimiser. Thus $m=\\boxed{\\tfrac1{16}}$."
        ]
      },
      {
        "name": "Trigonometric substitution: the cosine cannot stay small",
        "steps": [
          "Let $Q$ be any monic quintic and substitute $x=\\cos\\theta$, $\\theta\\in[0,\\pi]$, which sweeps $x$ over all of $[-1,1]$. Write the leading term as $\\cos^5\\theta$ and linearise powers of $\\cos\\theta$ into a cosine series: every monic quintic becomes $Q(\\cos\\theta)=2^{-4}\\cos5\\theta+\\sum_{j=0}^{4}b_j\\cos j\\theta$ for some reals $b_j$, because the only way to produce $\\cos5\\theta$ from $\\cos^5\\theta$ fixes its coefficient at $2^{-(5-1)}=\\tfrac1{16}$ (Chebyshev: $\\cos^5\\theta=\\tfrac1{16}\\cos5\\theta+\\tfrac5{16}\\cos3\\theta+\\tfrac58\\cos\\theta$), and lower monomials contribute no $\\cos5\\theta$.",
          "So $g(\\theta):=Q(\\cos\\theta)=\\tfrac1{16}\\cos5\\theta+R(\\theta)$ where $R$ is a trigonometric polynomial containing only the harmonics $\\cos j\\theta$, $j\\le4$. The point is that the top harmonic $\\cos5\\theta$ is locked at coefficient $\\tfrac1{16}$ no matter how the lower coefficients are chosen.",
          "Now isolate that $\\cos5\\theta$ coefficient by a DISCRETE projection at the six equioscillation nodes $\\theta_k=\\tfrac{k\\pi}{5}$, where $\\cos5\\theta_k=(-1)^k$. Take the weighted alternating sum $S=\\sum_{k=0}^{5}c_k\\,g(\\theta_k)$ with weights $c_k=(-1)^k\\,w_k$, $\\ (w_0,\\dots,w_5)=(\\tfrac12,1,1,1,1,\\tfrac12).$",
          "Discrete orthogonality of $\\{\\cos j\\theta_k\\}$ at these nodes makes every lower harmonic vanish: $\\sum_k c_k\\cos j\\theta_k=0$ for $0\\le j\\le4$, while $\\sum_k c_k\\cos5\\theta_k=\\sum_k w_k=5$. Hence only the $\\tfrac1{16}\\cos5\\theta$ part survives and $S=\\tfrac1{16}\\cdot5=\\tfrac{5}{16}$.",
          "Since $\\sum_k|c_k|=\\sum_k w_k=5$, the triangle inequality gives $\\tfrac{5}{16}=|S|=\\big|\\sum_k c_k g(\\theta_k)\\big|\\le \\lVert g\\rVert_\\infty\\sum_k|c_k|=5\\,\\lVert g\\rVert_\\infty$, hence $\\lVert Q\\rVert=\\lVert g\\rVert_\\infty\\ge\\tfrac1{16}$.",
          "Equality forces $|g(\\theta_k)|=\\tfrac1{16}$ with $g(\\theta_k)$ matching the sign of $c_k=(-1)^k w_k$ at all six nodes — i.e. $g$ equioscillates, which pins $Q=\\tfrac1{16}T_5$. Therefore $m=\\boxed{\\tfrac1{16}}$."
        ]
      },
      {
        "name": "Duality / extremal signed measure",
        "steps": [
          "The leading-coefficient functional is linear: for the difference of two monic quintics $D=P-Q$ we have $\\deg D\\le4$, so on the space $\\mathcal V$ of degree-$\\le4$ polynomials the problem ``minimise $\\lVert P-D\\rVert$ over $D\\in\\mathcal V$'' is a best-approximation problem, and $m$ equals the distance from $P=\\tfrac1{16}T_5$ to $\\mathcal V$ in sup-norm.",
          "Introduce the discrete signed measure $\\mu=\\sum_{k=0}^{5}w_k\\,\\delta_{x_k}$ at the nodes $x_k=\\cos\\tfrac{k\\pi}{5}$ with weights $w_k=(-1)^k\\lambda_k$, $\\lambda_k>0$, chosen so that $\\int v\\,d\\mu=0$ for every $v\\in\\mathcal V$ (such weights exist: $6$ nodes, $5$ linear conditions, one free scale — this is the Gauss-type annihilator of degree-$\\le4$ polynomials supported on $6$ points).",
          "Normalise $\\sum_k|w_k|=\\sum\\lambda_k=1$. Then for ANY monic quintic $Q$, write $Q=P-D$ with $D\\in\\mathcal V$; since $\\int D\\,d\\mu=0$, $\\int Q\\,d\\mu=\\int P\\,d\\mu=\\sum_k(-1)^k\\lambda_k\\,\\tfrac1{16}(-1)^k=\\tfrac1{16}\\sum_k\\lambda_k=\\tfrac1{16}.$",
          "Therefore $\\tfrac1{16}=\\big|\\int Q\\,d\\mu\\big|\\le \\lVert Q\\rVert\\sum_k|w_k|=\\lVert Q\\rVert$, giving $\\lVert Q\\rVert\\ge\\tfrac1{16}$ for every monic quintic. This is the dual lower bound.",
          "Equality forces $Q(x_k)$ to align in sign with $w_k$ and attain $\\pm\\lVert Q\\rVert$ at all six nodes, i.e. $Q$ equioscillates at $\\tfrac1{16}$; the only such monic quintic is $P=\\tfrac1{16}T_5$. Since $P$ realises $\\lVert P\\rVert=\\tfrac1{16}$, the bound is tight and $m=\\boxed{\\tfrac1{16}}$."
        ]
      }
    ],
    "remark": "This is the Chebyshev minimax theorem in miniature: $2^{1-n}T_n$ is the monic degree-$n$ polynomial of smallest sup-norm on $[-1,1]$, with minimum $2^{1-n}$ ($=\\tfrac1{16}$ for $n=5$). The single load-bearing fact is the count $n+1$: equioscillation at $n+1$ nodes turns a hypothetical better competitor's difference $D$ (degree $\\le n-1$) into a polynomial with $n$ sign changes, hence $n$ roots — one too many. Drop the multiple-angle identity and you lose the clean $\\pm1$ extrema; drop the monic constraint and the rival equioscillator $-2^{1-n}T_n$ sneaks back in. The three proofs are genuinely different mechanisms — Borel's root-counting, a trigonometric orthogonality/duality on $\\cos5\\theta$, and an extremal annihilating measure — but all pivot on the same $6$ alternation points the trap miscounts as $5$."
