          "Now apply $2+2\\cos\\varphi=4\\cos^{2}\\tfrac{\\varphi}{2}$ with $\\varphi=\\theta'=\\tfrac{2\\pi}{3}$, whose half $\\tfrac{\\pi}{3}$ has $\\cos\\tfrac{\\pi}{3}=\\tfrac12\\ge 0$: $\\sqrt{2+2\\cos\\tfrac{2\\pi}{3}}=\\sqrt{4\\cos^{2}\\tfrac{\\pi}{3}}=2\\bigl|\\cos\\tfrac{\\pi}{3}\\bigr|=2\\cos\\tfrac{\\pi}{3}=1$. (Numerically $\\sqrt{2+2(-\\tfrac12)}=\\sqrt{1}=1$, confirming the bars matter — the raw $2\\cos\\tfrac{8\\pi}{6}$ would have read $-1$.)",
