          "Prove the supporting-line inequality $f(A)\\ge L(A)$ for all $A\\in(0,\\pi)$ by tracking the gap $\\phi(A)=f(A)-L(A)$. By construction $\\phi(\\tfrac{\\pi}{3})=0$ and $\\phi'(\\tfrac{\\pi}{3})=f'(\\tfrac{\\pi}{3})-f'(\\tfrac{\\pi}{3})=0$, so $A=\\tfrac{\\pi}{3}$ is a stationary point of $\\phi$. The stationary points of $\\phi$ solve $f'(A)=L'(A)$, i.e. $\\dfrac{-4\\sin A}{(5-4\\cos A)^{2}}=-\\dfrac{2\\sqrt3}{9}$, equivalently $18\\sin A=\\sqrt3\\,(5-4\\cos A)^{2}$. Writing $c=\\cos A$ this is a cubic in $c$; on $(0,\\pi)$ it has exactly two roots, one at $A=\\tfrac{\\pi}{3}$ and one at $A_{0}\\approx 0.100$, and one checks $\\phi(A_{0})\\approx 0.283>0$ (a local maximum of the gap).",
          "Settle the sign of $\\phi$ from these two stationary points. At the endpoints $\\phi(0^{+})=f(0)-L(0)=1-L(0)\\approx 0.264>0$ (here $f(0)=\\tfrac{1}{5-4}=1$) and $\\phi(\\pi^{-})=f(\\pi)-L(\\pi)=\\tfrac19-L(\\pi)\\approx 0.584>0$ (here $f(\\pi)=\\tfrac{1}{5+4}=\\tfrac19$). With only the interior stationary values $\\phi(A_{0})\\approx 0.283>0$ and $\\phi(\\tfrac{\\pi}{3})=0$, the minimum of $\\phi$ on $[0,\\pi]$ is $0$, attained solely at $A=\\tfrac{\\pi}{3}$. Hence $f(A)\\ge L(A)$ on $(0,\\pi)$ with equality iff $A=\\tfrac{\\pi}{3}$. (Note the tangency survives the inflection of $f$ — this is exactly the strength of a supporting line over Jensen.)",
          "Sum over the three angles. Adding $f(A)\\ge L(A)$, $f(B)\\ge L(B)$, $f(C)\\ge L(C)$ and using $A+B+C=\\pi$, the linear corrections cancel: $\\sum L=3\\cdot\\tfrac13-\\dfrac{2\\sqrt3}{9}\\big((A+B+C)-\\pi\\big)=1-0=1$. Therefore $\\displaystyle\\sum \\frac{1}{1+8\\sin^{2}\\tfrac{A}{2}}=\\sum f\\ge \\sum L=1$, with equality exactly when $A=B=C=\\tfrac{\\pi}{3}$, i.e. the equilateral triangle, where each term is $\\tfrac13$. The minimum value is $\\boxed{1}$."
