          "Read off the deviation from $\\tfrac13$ exactly: $f-\\tfrac13=\\dfrac{1+t^{2}}{1+9t^{2}}-\\dfrac13=\\dfrac{3(1+t^{2})-(1+9t^{2})}{3(1+9t^{2})}=\\dfrac{2(1-3t^{2})}{3(1+9t^{2})}$. So each term exceeds $\\tfrac13$ precisely when $t<\\tfrac{1}{\\sqrt3}$ (i.e. $A<\\tfrac{\\pi}{3}$) and falls below when $A>\\tfrac{\\pi}{3}$ — a clean monotone profile in $t$ with no inflection issues, which is why a tangent line in the variable $A$ can support the curve globally.",
          "Establish the supporting line in this chart. The line $L(A)=\\tfrac13-\\tfrac{2\\sqrt3}{9}(A-\\tfrac{\\pi}{3})$ from Method 1 written via $A=2\\arctan t$ satisfies $f(A)-L(A)=\\dfrac{2(1-3t^{2})}{3(1+9t^{2})}+\\dfrac{2\\sqrt3}{9}\\big(2\\arctan t-\\tfrac{\\pi}{3}\\big)$, a single-variable function $\\psi(t)$ on $(0,\\infty)$ with $\\psi(\\tfrac{1}{\\sqrt3})=0$ and $\\psi'(\\tfrac{1}{\\sqrt3})=0$. Its derivative $\\psi'(t)=\\dfrac{-12t(1+9t^{2})-(1-3t^{2})\\cdot 18t}{3(1+9t^{2})^{2}}\\cdot\\tfrac23+\\dfrac{2\\sqrt3}{9}\\cdot\\dfrac{2}{1+t^{2}}$ vanishes only at $t=\\tfrac{1}{\\sqrt3}$ and one point near $t\\approx 0.050$, where $\\psi>0$; together with $\\psi(0^{+})\\approx 0.264>0$ and $\\psi(t)\\to-\\tfrac29+\\tfrac{2\\sqrt3}{9}\\cdot\\tfrac{2\\pi}{3}\\approx 0.584>0$ as $t\\to\\infty$ (the rational part tends to $\\tfrac19$ and the $\\arctan$ term saturates at $\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$), the only stationary value that touches zero is at $t=\\tfrac1{\\sqrt3}$, so $\\psi\\ge 0$ with equality only there.",
