    "remark": "The whole point is that ``equality at the centroid angle'' tempts you to reach for Jensen, but $f(A)=\\dfrac{1}{5-4\\cos A}$ has an inflection at $A^{*}\\approx 0.399$ and is concave on the short interval $(0,A^{*})$, convex on the long interval $(A^{*},\\pi)$ — so it is neither concave nor convex on all of $(0,\\pi)$, and global Jensen is simply unavailable in either direction. The tangent-line trick is the right tool exactly because it asks for less: not one-signed curvature everywhere, only that a single straight line drawn tangent at $A=\\tfrac{\\pi}{3}$ never rises above the curve. That weaker, global ``supporting-line'' condition can hold even across an inflection, which is why it routinely rescues symmetric triangle inequalities that defeat Jensen. The linear part of the tangent line is engineered to vanish on summation (the slope multiplies $\\sum(A-\\tfrac{\\pi}{3})=0$), so the constant $3\\cdot\\tfrac13=1$ is all that survives — that is the mechanical reason the bound is the clean integer $1$. Method 3's success is the tell-tale of which curvature is real: it works only after transferring the burden to $\\cos$, which genuinely is concave, via Cauchy-Schwarz and the classical $\\sum\\cos A\\le\\tfrac32$. The lesson for a top-rank student: before quoting Jensen on a symmetric inequality, compute the second derivative on the WHOLE feasible interval; if the sign flips, abandon Jensen and test whether the tangent at the symmetric point is a supporting line instead."
