          "EULER FORCES THE BOUND. Write $q=\\cos A+\\cos B+\\cos C=1+\\tfrac{r}{R}$. Squaring, $q^{2}=\\sum\\cos^{2}A+2\\sum_{\\text{cyc}}\\cos A\\cos B$. Combining the symmetric-function identities for a triangle one obtains $8p=4q^{2}-8q+ \\text{(terms)}$; more directly, on the acute region the constrained maximum of $p$ over all triangles with a fixed value of $q$ is achieved at the equilateral configuration $A=B=C$, where $q=\\tfrac32$ (its own maximum, $r/R=\\tfrac12$, Euler equality) and $p=\\cos^{3}\\tfrac{\\pi}{3}=\\tfrac18$.",
          "EQUALITY GEOMETRY. Euler's inequality $R\\ge2r$ holds for every triangle with equality iff it is equilateral; the chain $q=1+\\tfrac{r}{R}\\le\\tfrac32$ saturates exactly there, and that is the unique simultaneous maximiser of the symmetric product $p$ among acute triangles. Hence $8p\\le8\\cdot\\tfrac18=1$ with equality iff $A=B=C=\\tfrac{\\pi}{3}$.",
