    "remark": "The deciding fact is invisible until you ask for the SIGN: the right-angle boundary $\\{\\max(A,B,C)=\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}\\}$ is a zero-set of the product $\\cos A\\cos B\\cos C$, and the product is positive on acute triangles, zero on right triangles, negative on obtuse ones. So the inequality $8\\cos A\\cos B\\cos C\\le1$ is a genuine, equality-bearing statement ONLY on the acute side — everywhere else it is true for free because a negative (or zero) product is trivially below $1$. This is why every tempting one-liner is subtly defective: AM-GM on the three cosines is a non-negative-reals theorem and silently restricts you to acute triangles; the slick 'reduce to $\\sum\\cos^{2}\\ge\\tfrac34$ and apply Jensen' move dies on the same boundary, because $\\cos^{2}t$ is convex only on $[\\tfrac{\\pi}{4},\\tfrac{3\\pi}{4}]$ and any triangle with an angle below $45^{\\circ}$ — precisely the obtuse ones — falls outside the convex window, so the tangent line at $\\tfrac{\\pi}{3}$ overshoots and Jensen's direction is unjustified. The clean fix is mixing variables: freeze the largest angle, force $A=B$ by the product-to-sum estimate, and collapse to $8\\sin^{2}\\tfrac{C}{2}\\cos C=1-(4\\sin^{2}\\tfrac{C}{2}-1)^{2}$, a perfect square that hands you both the bound and the unique equilateral equality in one line. The lesson for a top-rank solver: before reaching for AM-GM or Jensen on trigonometric quantities, check the sign and the convexity window — a triangle bound that flips sign across the right angle cannot be proved by a tool that assumes positivity or global convexity, no matter how clean the final number looks."
