    "remark": "The whole problem hangs on separating a true statement from a true-sounding excuse. The constraint $\\sum\\cot A\\cot B=1$ is the constrained-quadratic-form skeleton: combined with the unconditional $\\sum x^{2}\\ge\\sum xy$ it yields $\\sum\\cot^{2}A\\ge1$ with no sign hypothesis whatsoever, so the prominently advertised word $acute$ is a decoy. Positivity of the cotangents is real but it only sharpens the auxiliary fact $\\sum\\cot A\\ge\\sqrt3$ — it is never invoked for the bound $\\ge1$. The genuinely surprising structure is the equality landscape: the floor $1$ is touched only at the equilateral triangle (forced by injectivity of $\\cot$ on $(0,\\pi)$), and as a triangle turns obtuse the sum is repelled upward past $2$, with infimum exactly $2$ at the unreachable right-isosceles limit. A top-rank student should leave with the meta-lesson that a stated hypothesis is not automatically load-bearing: always test whether the proof actually consumes it, and locate the equality case by tracking which monotone function pins the variables — here $\\cot$, not the cosine-product identity, which the problem was deliberately built to bypass.",
