    "trap": "The phantom is the printed bound $2$. It is obtained by the term-wise estimate $\\sec^{4}x\\ge1$ and $\\csc^{4}x\\ge1$, which are each true but cannot hold with equality $at the same$ $x$: $\\sec^{4}x=1$ forces $\\cos^{2}x=1$ (so $x=0$), while $\\csc^{4}x=1$ forces $\\sin^{2}x=1$ (so $x=\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$), and these two demands are mutually exclusive because $\\sin^{2}x+\\cos^{2}x=1$ cannot put all the mass on both ends at once. The fatal error is treating $\\sec^{2}x$ and $\\csc^{2}x$ as $independent$ free variables to be minimised separately; they are rigidly coupled, since with $u=\\sin^{2}x$ one has $\\sec^{2}x=\\tfrac{1}{1-u}$ and $\\csc^{2}x=\\tfrac{1}{u}$ tied by the single parameter $u\\in(0,1)$. Pushing $x$ toward $0$ to make $\\sec^{4}x\\to1$ sends $\\csc^{4}x\\to+\\infty$, so the sum races to $+\\infty$, not to $2$; symmetrically near $\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$. Thus $2$ is approached from neither side and is a strict, non-attainable underestimate. The honest optimum sits in the interior at the balance point $u=\\tfrac12$, i.e. $x=\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}$, where $\\sec^{4}\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}+\\csc^{4}\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}=(\\sqrt2)^{4}+(\\sqrt2)^{4}=4+4=8$. The subtlety is a missed-coupling / non-attainability trap, not an arithmetic slip: the naive chain loses sharpness exactly because it discards the constraint $\\sin^{2}x+\\cos^{2}x=1$ that binds the two reciprocals together.",
