    "remark": "This is a power-mean problem engineered so the laziest estimate is honest but useless. The term-wise bound $\\sec^{4}x\\ge1,\\ \\csc^{4}x\\ge1\\Rightarrow f\\ge2$ is a textbook example of losing sharpness by minimising coupled quantities independently: $\\sec^{2}x$ and $\\csc^{2}x$ are not free, they are tied through the lone parameter $u=\\sin^{2}x$ by $\\sin^{2}x+\\cos^{2}x=1$, and the two equality demands $\\cos^{2}x=1$ and $\\sin^{2}x=1$ live at opposite, incompatible endpoints. The instant one keeps the constraint — whether by reducing to $g(p)=(1-2p)/p^{2}$, by routing the inner sum through $\\sec^{2}x+\\csc^{2}x=4/\\sin^{2}2x\\ge4$, or by exploiting strict convexity of $u^{-2}+(1-u)^{-2}$ and the tangent line at the symmetry center — the dead bound $2$ is replaced by the attained value $8$ at $x=\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}$. The meta-lesson for a top-rank student: before celebrating a clean lower bound, test whether equality is $simultaneously$ achievable; an inequality whose equality cases are mutually exclusive is automatically non-sharp, and the true optimum will sit where the coupling is balanced, not where each piece is independently extreme.",
    "_meta_provenance": "min of sec^4 x+csc^4 x on (0,pi/2) is 8 at x=pi/4; naive term-wise bound 2 is true but non-attainable. Verified in sympy+numpy: f(pi/4)=8 exact, f'(pi/4)=0, f''(pi/4)=192>0; g(p)=(1-2p)/p^2 strictly decreasing (g'=2(p-1)/p^3<0) min 8 at p=1/4; QM-AM chain 1/2*(sec^2+csc^2)^2>=8 with sec^2+csc^2=4/sin^2(2x)>=4; F(u)=u^-2+(1-u)^-2 convex, F-8=(2u-1)^2(1+2u-2u^2)/(u^2(1-u)^2)>=0; 2e6 random points all >=8-1e-9."
