          "Therefore $\\sqrt2\\cdot\\tfrac{1}{\\sqrt2}\\le \\sin x+\\cos x\\le \\sqrt2\\cdot1$, i.e. $1\\le \\sin x+\\cos x\\le\\sqrt2$. The lower value $1$ occurs at the arc-ends, $x+\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}\\in\\{\\tfrac{\\pi}{4},\\tfrac{3\\pi}{4}\\}$, i.e. $x\\in\\{0,\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}\\}$; the upper value $\\sqrt2$ occurs at $x=\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}$.",
          "This independently confirms the floor $L=1$ with the same endpoint equality set, and exposes the trap quantitatively: the symmetric point $x=\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}$ is the $maximum$ $\\sqrt2$, never the minimum. So $\\boxed{L=1}$, equality iff $x\\in\\{0,\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}\\}$."
