    "remark": "The engine is a cancellation that is easy to miss: Jordan's chord $\\tfrac{2x}{\\pi}$ for $\\sin$ and Kober's chord $1-\\tfrac{2x}{\\pi}$ for $\\cos$ have opposite slopes $\\pm\\tfrac{2}{\\pi}$, so their sum is the constant $1$ — two slanted chords whose sum is a perfectly flat line. Because both $\\sin$ and $\\cos$ are strictly concave on $[0,\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}]$, each curve meets its chord $only$ at the chord's endpoints, and the two endpoint sets coincide at $\\{0,\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}\\}$; that shared simultaneity is precisely where $\\sin x+\\cos x$ touches its floor $1$. The instructive shock for a top-rank student is that equality is at the $asymmetric$ ends, while the symmetric point $x=\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}$ — the reflex ``balance'' candidate — is the $maximum$ $\\sqrt2$, where both chords are simultaneously $slack$. The meta-lesson: for a sum of concave terms bounded below by a constant, the minimiser lives at the boundary, not the centre; ``most symmetric'' is the equality case for $convex$ floors and Jensen-type upper bounds, but here the curvature points the other way. Finally, the problem forces honest use of $both$ chords at once — drop either and the surviving envelope collapses to $0$ at one endpoint — which is exactly the ``reason about two chords simultaneously'' skill the chapter is built to train.",
    "_meta_provenance": "Kober cos x >= 1-2x/pi (concavity, chord tight only at 0,pi/2) + Jordan sin x >= 2x/pi sum to the flat envelope 1; sin x + cos x >= 1 on [0,pi/2] with equality exactly at x=0,pi/2; trap point x=pi/4 is the MAX sqrt2 with both chords slack by 0.2071. Verified in numpy/mpmath/sympy: chord gaps vanish only at endpoints (interior min gap ~0.207), summed floor min=1 to 1e-43, amplitude and square-and-sign methods reproduce floor=1 and the same equality set, single-chord envelopes hit 0 at one endpoint."
