          "To see the ceiling $2$ fail directly: $f=2$ would force $\\sin 2x=1$ and $\\cos x=1$ simultaneously. But $\\cos x=1\\Rightarrow x\\equiv0\\Rightarrow\\sin 2x=0$, contradiction; and $\\sin 2x=1\\Rightarrow x\\equiv\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}\\Rightarrow\\cos x=\\tfrac{1}{\\sqrt2}\\ne1$. So equality in $|2\\sin2x\\cos x|\\le2$ is structurally impossible — the bound is never approached.",
          "Maximise honestly. With $u=\\cos^2 x\\in[0,1]$ and $\\sin x=\\sqrt{1-u}$ (taking $\\sin x\\ge0$ for the max branch), $f=4\\sqrt{1-u}\\,u$. By AM-GM on the three nonnegative parts $\\tfrac{1-u}{?}$ it is cleaner to optimise $f^2=16u^2(1-u)$: maximise $u^2(1-u)$ by AM-GM, $\\tfrac{u}{2}\\cdot\\tfrac{u}{2}\\cdot(1-u)\\le\\left(\\tfrac{u/2+u/2+(1-u)}{3}\\right)^3=\\tfrac1{27}$, so $u^2(1-u)\\le\\tfrac{4}{27}$, equality at $\\tfrac{u}{2}=1-u$, i.e. $u=\\tfrac23$, i.e. $\\cos^2x=\\tfrac23,\\ \\sin^2x=\\tfrac13$.",
