    "remark": "The engine is a frequency-mismatch illusion: $\\sin x+\\sin 3x$ looks like a sum of two independent waves, but $\\sin 3x$ is a $Chebyshev polynomial$ in $\\sin x$, so the whole expression secretly collapses to one cubic $4s-4s^3$ in $s=\\sin x$. Once that is seen, the extremum is forced to live where $g'(s)=4(1-3s^2)=0$, namely at the $irrational$ height $\\sin x=\\tfrac{1}{\\sqrt3}$ — which corresponds to no textbook angle, the precise reason every ``nice'' guess ($0,\\tfrac{\\pi}{6},\\tfrac{\\pi}{4},\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}$) misses. The headline trap, $2\\sin 2x\\cos x\\le2$, is the canonical coupled-product error: two factors sharing a variable cannot be peaked independently, and here the genuine maximum $\\tfrac{8\\sqrt3}{9}\\approx1.5396$ sits a clear distance below the phantom ceiling $2$. The three routes triangulate the same truth from different angles — Chebyshev calculus, an exact SOS factorisation $\\tfrac{4\\sqrt3}{9}(\\sqrt3 s-1)^2(\\sqrt3 s+2)$ that certifies the bound with no derivatives and pinpoints equality, and an AM-GM attack on $f^2=16u^2(1-u)$ that re-derives $\\cos^2x=\\tfrac23$. The lesson for a top-rank student: before bounding a trig sum factor-by-factor, check whether the harmonics are algebraically dependent; a higher harmonic of the same base angle is never a free wave, and its extremum may hide at an irrational value of the sine that no special-angle reflex will ever produce."
