    "remark": "Three independent ladders reach the same ceiling. The projection route is the structural one: the identity $a=b\\cos C+c\\cos B$ is the sine addition law wearing geometry, and summing it lands on $\\cos A+\\cos B+\\cos C=1+\\tfrac{r}{R}$ — which converts the seemingly trigonometric bound into Euler's $R\\ge 2r$, so $\\cos A+\\cos B+\\cos C\\le\\tfrac32$ is literally Euler's inequality in disguise. The lesson of the trap: a correct numerical answer can hide a broken proof. $\\cos$ flips from concave to convex at $\\pi/2$, so Jensen and the tangent-line trick silently fail for obtuse triangles; the completing-the-square and Schur arguments are honest because they never touch concavity. Whenever a triangle inequality is proved 'by Jensen on $\\cos$', check whether an obtuse angle has quietly left the concave region."
